Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)

library(GGally)

Load data

load("~/Dropbox/Pro Development/Stats with R/New Class/Linear and Multiple Regression Class/eaca_movies.Rdata") #load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data on movies released from 1970 to 2014 is taken from the site Rotten Tomatoes, which provides popular rankings for movies along with other information about them, as revealed in the codebook. The sample of 651 movies is randomly sampled, which makes it less than 10% of the movies made but still a large enough sample so that skew conditions may not be too much of an issue. In this case, because the sample size is large enough and randomly sampled, we are able to generalize beyond the sample to the general population for our predictions. Moreover, because this data is observational and not experimental, we cannot claim causality in the data.

As for other issues that we may face in using this data, because this is a website, we do have to contend with the fact that the results are limited to respondents who rated movies on the website, which may not be reflective of members who also rank films but may not be avid internet users (i.e., the non-response bias). Moreover, there does not seem to be the possibility that audience members are limited to voting once, but they could create and login with multiple email accounts to score a movie. Moreover, there might be concern on independence of film scores, especially if people in the same friendship group or household may be rating the same films in similar ways.

Part 2: Research question

My research question is the following:

Can we build a model that allows us to predict what makes a movie successful if we know other aspects about the movie, such as recipients of Academy Awards, run time, IMDB rating, and critics score?

This question is helpful in trying to figure out what are the characteristics of a well-received movie by the audience. This is not to imply causality, since this is not an experimental study. However, it is interesting to see in what ways critics scores and other variables, such as run time, may be correlated with audience scores since some of these factors could affect movie popularity and sales (especially run time, which has changed over time with many kinds of movies, like the longer run times of action movies).

It is also important to note that we are hoping to find, as an answer to our research question, a full model, rather than the most significant predictors, that can account for the response variable (audience score).

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Before we get into the data, let’s take a look at some histograms of our data to see the spread and distribution. We will look at critics score, run time, audience score (our response variable), and accolades from the Academy Awards (best picture nomination and if the film has an actor, actress, and director who has ever won an Academy Award).

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = movies$critics_score)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 15) #histogram of critics score

Looking at the histogram, we see that we have a unimodal peak, with some left skew (i.e., asymmetric data) for critics score. Let’s also take at some summary statistics.

summary(movies$critics_score)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1.00   33.00   61.00   57.69   83.00  100.00

From our summary statistics, we see that the median is greater than the mean, which we would expect because of the left skew. Moreover, we see that only 25% of the movies scored above 83, with the median critics score being 61.

This skew is also reflected in the normal probability plot below, which allows us to see that we have a little bit of a left tail, or some skewing. We also see that, because the line is not entirely straight, we would do well to not assume that this data follows a normal distribution, which is reflected in the histogram as well.

ggplot(data = movies, mapping = aes(sample = movies$critics_score)) + stat_qq() # normal probability plot for critics score

Let’s also do the same with our second variable of interest, the audience score.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = movies$audience_score)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) #histogram of audience score

Again, let’s observe that, while we do have a unimodal peak, we also have some left skewing in the data, which suggests that our median will be larger than the mean score. Let’s now calculate our summary statistics for audience score.

summary(movies$audience_score)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   11.00   46.00   65.00   62.36   80.00   97.00

Notice that, for the audience score, their median score is higher than that of the critics, but the difference is not as large. Also, for the audience score, note that no audience score goes above 97, whereas critics do rate movies up until 100. Moreover, the third quartile is lower for the audience than for critics.

ggplot(data = movies, mapping = aes(sample = movies$audience_score)) + stat_qq() # normal probability plot for audience score

The normal probability plot also shows a bit of left tail, or skew, which reflects the findings of the histogram. Moreover, from looking at this theoretical plot, we notice that the data is not necessarily follow a normal distribution because it does not have a straight line.

Let’s also do a side-by-side boxplot for the two groups to compare how they stack up against each other.

boxplot(movies$critics_score, movies$audience_score, names = c("Critics Score", "Audience Score"))

We notice that, for critics, there’s a more of a spread, which is what we saw in the summary statistics, than the audience. In essence, there’s a larger variability between the two groups, as evidenced by the length of the boxes (i.e., the IQR range) and the whiskers. For example, notice that the lower whisker for critics score extends much lower than that of the audience, whereas the upper whiskers are not too far off from each other. The medians for audience and critics score are also different, but they do not appear to be too far off from each other, as represented in the summary statistics as well.

Part 4: Modeling

Now that we have two variables established that we want to look at, let’s go ahead and create our model for this relationship. These variables for the full model were chosen because they seemed to me to be some of the items that everyday audiences might use to rate a movie as successful. The variables in the full model are run time, IMDB rating*, critics score, best picture win, best actor win, best actress win, best director win, and if the movie was in the top 200 box office.

*Note that IMDB rating may seem to be a measure of audience popularity since it appears to measure the same as the audience popularity score from Rotten Tomatoes. However, I’m assuming that, for some people, they may use the IMDB rating as something they check to decide if they will go and see a movie. A different model, though, might assume that these two are collinear and remove them.

movie_full <- lm(audience_score ~ runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_pic_nom + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies)

According to the full model, the full model explains about 75.51% of the data, and the most significant predictors seem to be critics score and IMDB rating. This full model does not include all the variables in the data set, for not all of them can be reasonably considered predictors (such as URL of the movie or release date), but are just meant to provide more context for the observations.

Just to exhaust the full model, let’s take a moment and calculate the estimates of our slope for some inference about the relationship of critics’ scores. First, let’s calculate a confidence interval at 95%. Do this, first let’s get our T critical value.

qt(.025, 641)
## [1] -1.963672

Note that our critical t value is 1.96, which is close to what we’d expect for a normal distribution because our degrees of freedom are so large. Nonetheless, let’s continue to calculate.

.06868 - 1.96 * .01984
## [1] 0.0297936
.06868 + 1.96 * .01984
## [1] 0.1075664

That said, we can be 95% confident that, for every 1 point increase in critics score, our audience score will be .03 to .10 points higher.

To find a model that is a better fit, we want to use a model that increases the adjusted R-squared value as much as possible from the full model (x > .7551). To do this, I used the backwards elimination approach, removing the value with the highest p-value (or the least significant predictor). In this case, the first variable to be removed was best picture win, and so on. In sum, here is the model I came up with.

NOTE: While it might be great to show the steps for the backwards elimination approach, this would take up more space. Instead, below I present the model that I came up with through elimination of variables: best picture win, best director win, and top200 box office.

m6 <- lm(audience_score ~ runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_pic_nom, data = movies)
summary(m6)

Note that our adjusted R-squared went up to .7556, or 75.6%. Thus, it’s not a huge increase, but it is an increase nonetheless from the full model.

While we’re at it, let’s also do a diagnositcs run to make sure it is appropriate for us to use the model. First, let’s do a residuals plot on the model to check for linearity.

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Fitted values") + ylab("Residuals")

Looking at our residuals plot, we see random scatter around 0, with no patterns in the residual plot, affirming that linear modeling is the right choice (i.e., constant variance of residuals). Let’s also do a check on the residuals with the histogram to check for nearly normal distribution of the residuals.

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = .resid)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

According to the histogram, we also see what appears to be a nearly normal distribution of the residuals, with a right skew. Let’s also check this condition using a normal probability plot.

ggplot(data = m6, aes(sample = .resid)) + stat_qq()

Our normal probability plot does not contain any long tails, so it seems we are in the clear for normal distribution of the residuals. Also, because these are sampled randomly, there seems to be no order effects we need to be concerned about.

Moreover, let’s also do a residuals plot for each predictor variable.

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = imdb_rating, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("IMDB Rating") + ylab("Residuals")

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = critics_score, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Critics Score") + ylab("Residuals")

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = best_actor_win, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Best Actor") + ylab("Residuals")

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = best_actress_win, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Best Actress") + ylab("Residuals")

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = best_pic_nom, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Best Pic Nom") + ylab("Residuals")

ggplot(data = m6, aes(x = runtime, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") + xlab("Run Time") + ylab("Residuals")

First, let’s take the residuals plot for the IMDB rating. For the lower ratings (under 4.0), we do tend to see positive residuals, and there also is a little less random scatter the higher the rating is. Nonetheless, there seems to be no major trend we need to be concerned with. This also may be because, within the data set, we have few films rated at a lower level below 4 and a greater number of films around 4.

For the residuals plot for critics score, we see a lot more random scater, which tells us that there are no underlying patterns we should be concerned with here. There do seem to be a few outliers in cases where there was a low score and a higher predicted value.

For the residuals versus ‘Best Actor,’ ‘Best Actress,’ ‘Best Pic Nomination,’ and ‘Best Director’ plots, note that we do see greater variability between the two groups (those who have won awards and those who have not). Thus, we do have a little more variability in these groups. In fact, the groups with no best actor, actress, best picture nomination, or director tend to show greater variability in the data.

Finally, for “run time”, there appears to be no underlying pattern here as well here, with no other patterns to account for (i.e., fan-shaped patterns).

Part 5: Prediction

Note above the movie values we have below for the score. Now let us create a data frame with those predictions. For our predicted movie, we will use Florence Foster Jenkins (2016), using data taken from IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes (searched 8/15/2016). The current IMDB rating is 7.2, the critics score from Rotten Tomatoes is 70. It also includes one best actress winner, Meryl Streep. The run time for the movie is 110 minutes.

m6 <- lm(audience_score ~ runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_pic_nom, data = movies)
Flo_Fos <- data.frame(runtime = 110, imdb_rating = 7.2, critics_score = 70, best_actor_win = "no", best_actress_win = "yes", best_pic_nom = "yes")
predict(m6, newdata=Flo_Fos)
##        1 
## 76.72177

Our prediction tells us that Florence Foster Jenkins, with the data characteristics, should have a 77.72 point approval score from the audience, which is quite high. (Note I am guessing on the nomination for best picture because the nominees haven’t been announced yet.)

Let’s also do a confidence interval check here as well for 95%.

predict(m6, Flo_Fos, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 76.72177 56.53099 96.91254

According to our model, we would be 95% confident that the score for audience popularity would be estimated between 56.53 and 96.91 (rounded up).

Part 6: Conclusion

For our project, we were tasked with helping our boss at Paramount Pictures to identify models that can help predict the success of a movie with the audience. In terms of success, we defined it in terms of the audience score as measured by Rotten Tomatoes, and we took a backwards-elimination approach to creating a model that helps us to predict success.

The model we created does allow us to account for about 75.56% of the observed data. Thus, we would tell our boss that run time, IMDB rating, critics score, best picture nomination, best actress and actor win would be the main things to consider in a model that could predict, about 75.6% of the time, audience’s popularity scores on movies. Again, it is important to note that overall this was a search for the best model, rather than specific predictors.
